'2022-01-29T02:06:57Z', 'updated_at': '2022-01-29T02:06:57Z', 'author_association': 'CONTRIBUTOR', 'body': '> @iambmelt Your remotes should look more like this:
> 
> ```shell
> marsh@marsma-win:~/repos/azure-docs-pr$ git remote -v
> origin  git@github.com:mmacy/azure-docs-pr.git (fetch)
> origin  git@github.com:mmacy/azure-docs-pr.git (push)
> upstream        git@github.com:MicrosoftDocs/azure-docs-pr.git (fetch)
> upstream        git@github.com:MicrosoftDocs/azure-docs-pr.git (push)
> ```
> 
> Process is:
> 
> 1. **fork** private repo `azure-docs-pr` - now you have _iambmelt/azure-docs-pr_
> 2. clone your **fork** - this is now (or should be, in your case) your `origin` remote
> 3. add _MicrosoftDocs/azure-docs-pr_ (not your fork) as `upstream` **remote**
> 4. create local working **branch**
> 5. make changes
> 6. push branch to your **fork**
> 7. issue PR from your **fork** _iambmelt/azure-docs-pr_ to **"upstream"** repo _MicrosoftDocs/azure-docs-pr_

Gotcha - thanks Marsh!', 'reactions': {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/MicrosoftDocs/azure-docs/issues/comments/1024807757/reactions', 'total_count': 0, '+1': 0, '-1': 0, 'laugh': 0, 'hooray': 0, 'confused': 0, 'heart': 0, 'rocket': 0, 'eyes': 0}, 'performed_via_github_app': None}}

Here's what I'm actually doing...

Clone the private repo:
```
git clone https://github.com/MicrosoftDocs/azure-docs-pr.git
```

Make my own branch:
```
git checkout -b iambmelt/obo-warning
```

// Do local edits

Commit my work:
```
git add .
git commit -m "blah blah"
```

Push it back to the origin on my named branch:
```
git push --set-upstream origin iambmelt/obo-warning
```

Just to sanity check myself, this is remote url:
```
$ git config --get remote.origin.url
